Cooking Time:

Cuisine: 

#### INGREDIENTS 

* 3 cups All-Purpose Flour 
* 2 tsp salt 
* 1 egg
* 1 cup Water, added little by little 
  
#### STOVE-TOP DIRECTIONS 

For the Dough: 

1. In a large bowl, mix flour, salt, and oil. Slowly add water, a little bit at a time, mixing with your hands until soft dough forms. Note: Depending on the brand of the flour you may need more or less water so only add a little bit at a time.
2. Add oil to the dough and knead for 4 to 5 minutes until the dough is smooth. Rest the dough for 10 to 20 minutes covered with plastic wrap or in an airtight container.
3. Divide the dough into ten pieces and roll each piece on the palm of your hands into a round ball.



Rolling a Square Paratha: 

1. Take one piece of the dough ball and dip it in the dry flour lightly coating it all over with flour. Using a rolling pin, roll the dough into a  4-inch circle. Dip one side of the circle into the flour. Drizzle the floured surface with few drops of oil, spread it evenly with your fingers.
2. Fold top 1/3 side of the circle to the center. Fold bottom 1/3 side of the circle to the center. Drizzle the surface with few drops of oil, spread it evenly with your fingers, and fold the left 1/3 side to the center and the right 1/3 side to the center. This will form a square-shaped piece of dough layered with oil and flour.
3. Dip the square-shaped dough in dry flour coating both sides generously with flour. Next, roll the dough back and forth with the rolling pin as you maintain the square shape. Check the video in the recipe card for more details on the rolling.

Rolling a Triangle Paratha: 

1. ake one piece of the dough ball and roll it in the dry flour. Using a rolling pin, roll the dough into a  6-inch circle.
2. Dip one side of the circle into the flour.
3. Drizzle the floured surface with few drops of oil, spread it evenly with your fingers.
4. Fold the circle in half so that the oil is on the inside.
5. Drizzle the surface with few drops of oil, spread it evenly with your fingers.
6. Fold the semicircle in half again to form a triangle-shaped piece of dough layered with flour and oil.
7 Dip the dough in the dry flour to generously coat both sides.
8 Roll the dough back and forth with the rolling pin as you maintain the triangle shape. Check the videos for more details on the rolling.

Rolling a Circle Paratha: 


Cooking a Paratha: 
Warm a griddle over medium-high heat. Once the griddle is hot, carefully place the rolled out paratha on the surface and cook until the bottom of the paratha turns lighter than the uncooked top, about 1 minute.
With a flat spatula, flip the paratha and top with ghee, spreading it evenly over the surface with the back of the spoon. Cook the second side until it turns light brown, about 2 minutes.
Flip the paratha and top with ghee, spreading it evenly over the surface. Cook until light brown, 1 to 2 minutes.
Gently press the paratha with the spatula to help the paratha cook evenly; be sure to press gently for a soft, flaky paratha. Once both sides get spotty golden brown, transfer the paratha to a plate.
Repeat with the remaining dough pieces, oil, and ghee. While one paratha is cooking you can start to roll the next. Enjoy warm!

### ABOUT THE MEAL

Parathas are homemade Indian flatbreads typically cooked daily to be enjoyed for breakfast, lunch, or dinner. Parathas are made by layering and rolling dough that is then cooked on a hot griddle until it turns golden brown on both sides. They fill your kitchen with the wonderful aroma of freshly made bread with the ghee melting over.

